    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two particles become linked, so the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. This is different from classical correlation, where two objects might be related, but their states are independent of each other. Imagine two entangled particles as a pair of magical, talking twins who always know what the other is thinking, even if they're on opposite sides of the universe. In contrast, classical correlation is like two friends who share a secret handshake, but they can still act independently. The magic twins (entangled particles) always stay in sync, while the friends (classically correlated objects) can go their separate ways.",
